[1
Connecticut
-----------
State of Connecticut Mosquito Management Program
<http://dep.state.ct.us/mosquito/index.asp>
On 25 Sep 2000, The State Mosquito Management Program has temporarily
suspended ground-level spraying for the control of mosquitoes in the state.
The DEP, DPH, and CAES have consulted and agreed to postpone ground
application to control mosquitoes which was scheduled for Tuesday, September
26 in Stamford and parts of Darien due to concerns about adverse weather
conditions. Spraying scheduled in Meriden for 25 Sep 2000 has been postponed
at the request of city officials. The State has not withdrawn its
recommendation to spray these affected communities. When temperatures are
below 50 degrees mosquito activity decreases, making ground level spraying
less effective. Current weather forecasts for the remainder of the week
present unfavorable conditions; wind, rain and cooler evenings, which will
effectively reduce current mosquito populations.
On 25 Sep 2000, the state announced the finding of a crow positive for West
Nile Virus in the town of Manchester. No spraying is currently planned in
the town of Manchester.
******
New York City
-------------
New York City Dept. of Health Press Release
<http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/doh/html/public/press00/pres2000.html> [edited
On Sat 23 Sep 2000, New York City Health Commissioner Neal L. Cohen, M.D.,
announced today that a 52 year-old Staten Island man has tested positive for
West Nile virus (WNV). The individual, who lives in Greenridge, Staten
Island, was admitted to the hospital on September 19 with encephalitis,
after having experienced flu-like symptoms for several weeks. He is
currently hospitalized in stable condition, and is improving. The laboratory
results were obtained by tests performed at the New York City Department of
Health's (NYCDOH) laboratories, and specimens have been sent to the U.S.
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) for further confirmation. A
total of 12 people have been diagnosed with West Nile virus in New York City
in 2000. "While the peak of the mosquito season in New York City has passed,
and we will see fewer mosquitoes as temperatures drop, we are still finding
evidence of West Nile virus through our ongoing surveillance activities, and
an additional human illness at this time of year is not surprising," Dr.
Cohen said.
Bird and Mosquito Findings
The positive WNV findings announced today include: in Queens, one bird, a
veery (a member of the thrush family) collected in Forest Hills on 10 Sep
2000. In Brooklyn, one mosquito pool collected from Dyker eights on 9 Sep
2000. On Staten Island, 4 mosquito pools: one collected from Richmond
Valley on 12 Sep 2000; one collected from the Silver Lake area on 12 Sep
2000; one collected from Tottenville on 12 Sep 2000; and one collected from
Westerleigh on 6 Sep 2000.
******
New York State
---------------
New York State West Nile Virus Updates and Maps
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.htm>
On 25 Sep 2000, the New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Center
laboratories reported 2 West Nile virus positive dead birds in the following
counties: Albany, 1 and Schenectady, 1.
Two West Nile virus positive mosquito pools were found in the following
counties: New York City, 2 (Brooklyn, 1 and Staten Island, 1).
One human West Nile virus case was found in New York City (Staten Island).
The total West Nile virus positive results to date are: Dead birds - 841;
mosquito pools - 288; sentinel chickens - 1; live wild birds - 7; mammals
(excluding humans)s - 20; humans - 12 (3 Brooklyn, 9 Staten Island).
