[2
Date: Mon, 25 Sep 2000 08:34:31 -0400
From: Walter J. Tabachnick <wjt@GNV.IFAS.UFL.EDU>

Surveillance data
------------------
I implore ProMED-mail to require that postings of West Nile "positives"
include the diagnostic test used. ProMED-mail has continued to spread
reports of the presence of West Nile virus based on reports that are
probably based on PCR and/or serologic diagnostics. Is this so? Where have
there been virus isolations? Have there been attempts at virus isolations
that failed? Where? What diagnostic is the basis for determining the
presence of West Nile virus in a specific region? We are being deluged by
imprecise reports of "positives."
One would have thought this information would be forthcoming to allow
readers to interpret the meaning of the numerous West Nile virus reports.
The absence of this information has caused considerable confusion. The
finding of a PCR positive or serologic positive bird in Canada does not
necessarily mean that West Nile virus has spread to Canada.
--
Walter J. Tabachnick
Florida Medical Entomology Laboratory
University of Florida
200 9th St, SE
Vero Beach, FL 32968
<wjt@GNV.IFAS.UFL.EDU>
[Dr. Tabachnick raises some important issues. Unfortunately the nature of
the diagnostic tests are rarely communicated and there are not enough hours
in the day for ProMED-mail moderators and editors to ferret out the
information. - Mod.CP
