[3
Date: Thurs. 21 Sept 2000 1749 MDT
From: Charles H. Calisher <calisher@promedmail.org>

West Nile virus, inappropriate optimism
---------------------------------------
Is it interesting to anyone else that not a single predictor of the
emergence and spread of West Nile virus has been useful? In New York City,
authorities (or perhaps "spokespeople" would be a better term), who were not
able even to make a misdiagnosis of St. Louis encephalitis, leaving that to
CDC instead, spoke of containing West Nile virus and hoped the virus would
not overwinter in the harsh climate of the northeastern U.S. It overwintered
quite nicely.
When cases began occurring in Staten Island (Borough of Richmond) this year
the spokespeople were quick to point out that the probable dates of
infection of those cases were before insecticide spraying/vector control
began. No one has since announced that recent cases likely were infected
after such control programs began.
New Jersey spokespeople indicated that, because of the excellence of their
mosquito control program, there would likely be no human infections due to
West Nile virus in New Jersey. So much for that prediction.
Although West Nile virus has spread from the apparent epicenter in New York
City and has been found from near [and across? the Canadian border to near
all other state lines, West Nile virus has not been found in Pennsylvania,
suggesting that birds are not crossing the state line.
An Israeli spokesperson was quoted in various media sources (and posted on
ProMED-mail) that West Nile virus occurs with some regularity in Israel and
that the government was not planning on panicking, as "the people of New
York had done". This morning's newspaper carried a story about 13 deaths and
thousands of cases of West Nile virus there and that a "state of emergency"
has been declared. [The Israeli outbreak has been designated an "epidemic"
and "not-an-epidemic" in quick succession by Israeli spokespeople with
different agendas. - Mod.CP
The expansion of West Nile virus habitat to North American cities clearly
has underlined what many of us have been saying for years, that short shrift
has been paid to arbovirology, to the training of medical entomologists, and
to the epidemiology of vector-borne diseases. That sentinel chickens are
useless as indicators of West Nile virus activity (why?), that the
southwestern border of New York State is as far as the virus has been found
in that region (why?), that the virus has not spread further south than
Maryland (why not?), that outbound migratory birds last year did not take
the virus with them to Florida and Latin America (why not?), that we
obviously do not know what the vectors are as this virus adapts to its new
ecosystem (why not?). It is likely that the control programs that have been
employed have been less a factor this year than have the natural conditions
in the northeastern U.S. Worst of all this, not a single prediction has been
correct.
Here are two predictions: As West Nile virus expands further and probes even
more eco-niches in the U.S., it will infect more arthropod vectors, and kill
more humans, horses, wild birds, bats, pet rabbits, and domestic animals.
That everyone who makes a prediction about this virus in North America,
without any knowledge whatsoever, will be shown to be wrong.
Education and training are needed, not more people with suits.
--
Charles H. Calisher, Ph.D.
<calisher@promedmail.org>
[Dr. Calisher has highlighted many important issues regarding the
epidemiology of West Nile virus infection in North America, and concerning
the management of information. I have edited Dr. Calisher's contribution to
make it conform with certain aspects of ProMED-mail policy. If anyone feels
short-changed, the full text is available from the source. In defence of
spokespeople, it should be recognized that very often they are merely acting
on inadequate and equivocal information provided by their scientific and
medical advisors. - Mod.CP
